{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":14541,"record_hash":"sha256:b6f15c3ad9c6d406396938f6b19595a4b6477713a71c39e59e21f8fcf3a9befd","timestamp":"2026-05-09T17:56:14.563Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 7979e6\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 1886\nOutput:\n# GitMeta Data Model\n\n## Principles\n\n- Store durable agent sessions on the `project` target by default.\n- Use shareable-ready `gitbutler:*` keys for GitButler agentlog data.\n- Do not use `meta:local:*` for the main session records; GitMeta treats local\n  keys as never serialized.\n- Redact all copied transcript strings before writing.\n- Keep branch, pull request, change, and commit links as future references to\n  durable project sessions, not owners of session data.\n- Do not write standard `agent:*` keys until there is an interoperability or\n  publication contract.\n- Do not call GitMeta serialize, push, fetch, or sync in the POC.\n\nGitMeta stores metadata as `(target, key, value)` tuples. Supported target types\ninclude `commit`, `change-id`, `branch`, `path`, and `project`. Keys are\nnamespace-like strings split on `:`, and list values are append-friendly logs.\n\n## Standard Agent Keys\n\nGitMeta recommends keys such as:\n\n```text\nagent:provider\nagent:model\nagent:session-id\nagent:prompt\nagent:summary\nagent:transcript\n```\n\nThese are likely future interoperability keys, but they are not first-POC\nstorage. The POC writes GitButler-owned keys only.\n\n## POC Storage Model\n\nFor the first implementation, write to `project` unless `--target` is explicit.\n\nSession index:\n\n```text\ngitbutler:agent-sessions = set<session-key>\n```\n\nDurable session prefix:\n\n```text\ngitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:*\n```\n\nSession-level keys:\n\n```text\ngitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:schema = gitbutler.agent-session.v1\ngitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:updated-at = <capture timestamp>\ngitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:sources = set<source-key>\ngitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:record-hashes = set<sha256:record>\ngitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:transcript = list<TranscriptEnvelope JSON>\n```\n\nSource-level keys:\n\n```text\ngitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:source:<source-key>:agent\ngitbutler:agent-session:<session-key\n[TRUNCATED]\n commit, change, or PR targets. Store\nrelationship keys there later; keep the transcript itself on the durable project\nsession.\n\n## Deduplication\n\nUse stable record hashes:\n\n```text\nsha256(trimmed raw JSONL line bytes)\n```\n\nThe session-level `record-hashes` set tracks metadata dedupe. Transcript append\ndedupe is rebuilt from the stored envelope list by reading each envelope's\n`record_hash`. This keeps transcript backfill possible if the list is missing\nwhile the record hash set still exists.\n\nRepeat capture of the same session should:\n\n- write no duplicate transcript envelopes\n- append only newly observed records when a transcript grows\n- keep source provenance keys up to date once per successful capture\n\n## Future Association Model\n\nDo not attach transcript data directly to branches, commits, changes, or pull\nrequests in the POC. The project session is the durable object.\n\nLater, when GitButler has an explicit target, write relationship references:\n\n```text\n<branch/change/commit target>\n  gitbutler:agent-sessions = set<session-key>\n```\n\nThis supports:\n\n- one session contributing to multiple branches or pull requests\n- multiple sessions contributing to one branch or pull request\n- sessions that exist before any code or branch association\n\nSee [Future Use Cases](future-use-cases.md) for the product scenarios this\nsupports.\n\n## Serialization\n\nThe POC does not call GitMeta serialize, push, fetch, or sync. It writes\nshareable-ready keys but leaves remote exchange for a later integration with\nexplicit privacy and product behavior.\n\n## Redaction\n\nAll stored agentlog values copied from transcripts are redacted before writing.\nThe POC uses a small guard for sensitive field names, high-entropy strings,\nUUID-shaped values, and random-looking long hex strings. This is intentionally\nnot a complete secret scanner; it is a pragmatic safety net for the first data\nshape.\n\nFuture work may add repository settings, user confirmation, stronger scanners,\nor destination-specific publication filters before metadata is exchanged.\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-09T17:56:14.563Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}